Perspectives on processes by which Catholic church attained primacy in urban spaces of colonial Mexico. Contributors examine institutional relations and aspects of church-city relations, based on three thematic divisions: church's role in conformation and appropriation of urban spaces, ecclesiastical social institutions and their presence in cities, and importance of culture and symbolism produced by corporations and agents linked to religious knowledge.

Narrates 40-year history of teachers' college in Zacatecas dedicated to rural schoolteachers. Transcribes, annotates and studies late 15th-century incunabulum that translates to Spanish 13th century Latin manuscript containing calendar of saints' days with details of saints' lives. Transcription is only slightly modernized and preserves most archaic spellings and grammar. First 150 pages are critical study of manuscript, its historical context, linguistic peculiarities, history of publication, and its transmission to and comparison with subsequent hagiographies. Includes reproductions of original woodcut engravings.

Analyzes creation of local, anti-crime vigilante movements known as "Autodefensas" that have emerged in recent decades to counter widespread narco-violence and police corruption. Based on case studies in states of Guerrero and Michoacan, authors shed light on specificities and heterogeneity of such groups, noting ways in which they subvert traditional concepts of power, state, capitalism and resistance.

Study of ceramic artifacts dating from Late Classic age recovered from sealed environments (funeral and ritual sites) in ancient Mayan city of Yaxchilan, Chiapas. Suggests information on social status associated with this type of ceramic, plus delves into production methods and source of raw materials for both local and imported ceramics.

Important new analysis of much-studied pre-Classic archaeological site in northern central Veracruz. Study focuses on city's relationship to other sites and to other societies of its time. Supported by wealth of archaeological detail, relates political organization of city-state with respect to governments of Teotihuacan (in central Mexico) and to those of gulf and Mayan states. Posits that El Tajin and its associated societies are situated within tradition of great Mesoamerican civilizations in which governors based their power and privilege on religious ideology that established them as divine intermediaries.

un análisis de por qué y cómo la reforma electoral de 1996 desencadenó la caída del régimen priista /

Prólogo -- Introduccíon -- ¡El maldesempeño económico explica el fin de losregímenes de partido dominante? -- Teoría de la migracíon clientelar :explicacíon del fin del régimen de partido dominante del PRI -- ¡Por qúe la reforma de 1996 desencadenó el fin de régimen de partido dominante encabezado por el PRI? -- ¡Por qúe se propuso yaprobó la reforma electoral del 1996? -- Conclusiones.

"La reforma definitiva propone una neuvaexplicación sobre el fin del régimen autoritario que el Partido Revolucionario Institucional (PRI) encabezó enMéxico, entre 1929 y 2000. Para el autor, la reforma electoral de 1996 tuvo un papel clave. Los profundos cambios en la estructura de incentivos de las facciones priistas con esta reforma desencadenaron la erosión de launidad del partido y, con ello, la deserción de sus cuadrosmás experimentados y sus valiosas máquinas clientelares."
